<?xml version="1.1" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<databaseChangeLog
    xmlns="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog
        http://www.liquibase.org/xml/ns/dbchangelog/dbchangelog-3.6.xsd">

    <!--
        Phase E.6 Tier 1 — ophthalmology-domain subject extension.

        Ophthalmology trials systematically scope each enrolled subject
        to ONE eye (or both) for the study endpoints, because most
        interventions (intravitreal injections, lens implants, gonio
        surgery, etc.) target a single eye. Recording this at the
        study_subject level avoids re-asking it on every visit form and
        gives the matrix / exports a single source of truth.

        Two new columns:

          - `study_eye` VARCHAR(3): the study-eye scope. Allowed values
            'OD' (right), 'OS' (left), 'OU' (both). NULL is permitted
            (non-ophth studies, or pre-screening before randomization).
            Deliberately NO Postgres ENUM / CHECK constraint — enum
            evolution in Postgres is painful (ALTER TYPE ... ADD VALUE
            can't run in a transaction; rename / drop is multi-step
            with downtime); enforcement lives in the Java DTO
            validator + SPA SelectInput options. This matches the
            project's existing pattern (gender stored as char without
            a CHECK).

          - `screening_date` DATE: the date the subject was screened
            for eligibility — typically 1-30 days before
            `enrollment_date`. Optional because non-MUW deployments
            may run studies without a screening visit, and because
            data for retrospective imports is sometimes missing.

        Both columns are nullable + un-defaulted: this changeset is
        context-FREE (runs on every install, demo + production +
        on-prem) and must not invalidate any existing row.

        No CHECK constraint at the DB level because:
          1) study_eye enum evolution would be painful for future
             extensions like 'BIL' / 'XX' / per-arm overrides.
          2) screening_date <= enrollment_date is a logical rule, but
             enforcing it as a CHECK breaks legacy imports where
             screening_date is later than enrollment by 1-2 days due
             to administrative dating differences. Java + SPA enforce
             the validator-friendly version of the rule.
    -->
    <changeSet author="muw-ophthalmology" id="2026-06-05-ophth-subject-eye-and-screening-date">
        <preConditions onFail="MARK_RAN">
            <and>
                <not><columnExists tableName="study_subject" columnName="study_eye"/></not>
                <not><columnExists tableName="study_subject" columnName="screening_date"/></not>
            </and>
        </preConditions>
        <addColumn tableName="study_subject">
            <column name="study_eye" type="VARCHAR(3)">
                <constraints nullable="true"/>
            </column>
            <column name="screening_date" type="DATE">
                <constraints nullable="true"/>
            </column>
        </addColumn>
    </changeSet>
</databaseChangeLog>
